---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'why-morocco', text: 'Why Retirees Choose Morocco', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-residency', text: 'Visa & Residency', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-access', text: 'Healthcare Access', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Cost Planning', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Spain for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/spain' },
  { title: 'Portugal for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/portugal' },
  { title: 'Senior Insurance', href: '/best/senior-insurance' },
  { title: 'France for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/france' },
  { title: 'Budget Expat Insurance', href: '/best/budget-expat-insurance' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'ageLimit', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'preExisting', header: 'Pre-Existing' },
  { key: 'moroccoNetwork', header: 'Morocco Network' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly (Age 60)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Covered (24mo wait)', moroccoNetwork: 'Good', monthly: '$280-420' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Moratorium option', moroccoNetwork: 'Good', monthly: '$260-400' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', ageLimit: '70', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', moroccoNetwork: 'Excellent (French connections)', monthly: '$270-410' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', ageLimit: '74', preExisting: 'Case-by-case', moroccoNetwork: 'Adequate', monthly: '$220-360' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'item', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'notes', header: 'Notes' },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: 'International Insurance (55-59)', monthly: '$220-340', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (60-64)', monthly: '$280-420', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$380-550', notes: 'Comprehensive coverage' },
  { item: 'Local Moroccan Insurance', monthly: '1,500-3,000 MAD', notes: '~$150-300 local coverage' },
  { item: 'Direct medical costs', monthly: '300-800 MAD', notes: '~$30-80 routine care' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in Morocco | Residency Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for retirees in Morocco. Residency options, Marrakech and coastal living, healthcare access, and costs for European and American retirees."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in Morocco"
  subheadline="Morocco offers exotic culture just 3 hours from Europe—at a fraction of European prices. French-speaking, improving healthcare, and established expat communities make it accessible. Here's the practical guide."
  heroImage="/images/countries/default-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Retiree Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mb-4">
    <strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> We may earn a commission when you click our links and purchase insurance. This doesn't affect our recommendations or the price you pay.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Overview</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Morocco has attracted European retirees for decades—French expats in particular have made it a second home. Marrakech, Essaouira, and coastal cities offer exotic charm at affordable prices, all within a 3-hour flight from London or Paris. The culture is fascinating, the climate excellent, and the cost of living remarkably low.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Healthcare is improving but uneven. Casablanca and Rabat have good private hospitals; smaller cities are more limited. Many retirees use Morocco for routine care while planning Spain or France for serious conditions. International insurance with European coverage is the practical approach.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Key Facts for Retirees</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> 90-day visa-free (most nationalities), renewable residence available</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance required:</strong> For residence applications; essential for healthcare</li>
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Improving private sector; Europe backup for complex cases</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of living:</strong> 60-70% lower than Western Europe</li>
      <li><strong>Languages:</strong> French (widely spoken), Arabic (official), some Spanish</li>
      <li><strong>Proximity:</strong> 3 hours to most European capitals</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-morocco" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Why Retirees Choose Morocco</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Exceptional Affordability</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    A comfortable retirement in Morocco costs $1,200-2,000/month—60-70% less than Western Europe. Marrakech riads (traditional houses) rent for $500-1,000/month. Domestic help is $200-300/month. Dining out is cheap. Your European pension buys a significantly higher quality of life here.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Proximity to Europe</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Marrakech is 3 hours from London, Paris, or Madrid. Tangier has ferry connections to Spain. For retirees wanting exotic retirement but not wanting to be far from Europe, Morocco is ideal. Weekend visits to family, European healthcare when needed, easy travel—all accessible.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Climate Variety</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Morocco offers diverse climates. Marrakech is warm and dry (like Arizona). Essaouira has coastal breezes (cooler, windier). Agadir offers beach climate. The Atlas Mountains provide cooler retreats. Unlike single-climate destinations, you can choose what suits you.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cultural Richness</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Morocco is genuinely different—medinas, souks, traditional architecture, Islamic culture, French colonial influence. For retirees seeking cultural immersion rather than expat bubble living, it delivers. English-speaking communities exist but you'll engage with local culture daily.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-residency" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Visa & Residency</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Visa-Free Entry</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Citizens of most Western countries (US, UK, EU, Canada, Australia) can enter Morocco visa-free for 90 days. Many retirees simply exit to Spain or elsewhere and return for another 90 days. This works indefinitely but doesn't provide official residency status.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Residence Card (Carte de Séjour)</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For official residency, apply for a carte de séjour at the local police station. Requirements: proof of income (pension statements), accommodation proof (rental contract or property), and health insurance. Initial card valid 1 year, renewable. After 5 years, eligible for permanent residence.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Income Requirements</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    No specific minimum income stated, but you must demonstrate sufficient funds to support yourself. Pension income is ideal. Bank statements showing regular deposits help. The bar is relatively low—Morocco wants retirees spending money locally.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Property Route</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Buying property simplifies residency. Property ownership demonstrates commitment and investment. Many retirees purchase riads in Marrakech or coastal apartments. Property prices are reasonable—quality riads from $150,000-400,000 in good locations.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Morocco Insurance?"
    description="Get coverage that meets residency requirements and includes European healthcare access."
    buttonText="Get Morocco Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Insurance Requirements</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">For Residence Applications</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Residence card applications require proof of health insurance valid in Morocco. International health insurance from major providers satisfies this requirement. Some local Moroccan insurers also qualify. Documentation should show your name, coverage dates, and Morocco coverage.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">European Coverage Is Essential</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Given Morocco's healthcare limitations for complex conditions, your insurance should cover treatment in Europe—particularly Spain and France (closest major medical hubs). A 2-hour flight to Madrid or Barcelona accesses world-class hospitals. Ensure your policy covers EU treatment without excessive restrictions.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What to Look For</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Prioritize: Morocco coverage (for routine care), EU coverage (for serious conditions), medical evacuation, inpatient and outpatient coverage, and pre-existing condition coverage if applicable. Policies covering Morocco + Europe provide the practical safety net retirees need.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pre-Existing Conditions</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Cigna offers guaranteed acceptance with 24-month waiting period. Allianz offers moratorium underwriting. AXA (with strong French connections and Morocco presence) reviews case-by-case. For those with conditions, comprehensive coverage is especially important—Moroccan hospitals have limitations.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Recommended Providers</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">AXA Global — Best for Morocco</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    AXA has significant presence in Morocco (AXA Assurance Maroc) and strong French connections. This means excellent local relationships and smooth coordination between Moroccan and French healthcare. Good network in both Morocco and Europe. Natural choice for French-speaking retirees.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cigna Global — Best Overall</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Global network with Morocco and European coverage. Guaranteed acceptance option covers pre-existing conditions after 24 months. Worldwide coverage for travel. Higher premiums but comprehensive. Good for retirees who travel frequently or may relocate.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Allianz Care — European Focus</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Strong European networks with adequate Morocco coverage. Moratorium underwriting option for pre-existing conditions. Competitive pricing. Good choice for those planning to use European hospitals for serious care.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Local Moroccan Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Saham Assurance, Wafa Assurance, and Atlanta offer local coverage at 1,500-3,000 MAD/month (~$150-300). These cover Moroccan hospitals but not European care. May satisfy residence requirements but insufficient for retirees wanting European healthcare backup.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Morocco Insurance Options"
    description="See actual costs for your age and situation. No obligation quotes."
    buttonText="Get Personalized Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-access" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Healthcare Access in Morocco</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Private Hospitals</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Casablanca has the best facilities: Clinique du Parc, Hôpital Cheikh Khalifa, Clinique Atfal. Rabat has several good private clinics. Marrakech has Clinique Internationale and Polyclinique du Sud. Quality is improving but uneven. French-trained doctors are common. English availability varies.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">The European Backup</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For complex conditions—cardiac surgery, cancer treatment, major trauma—Spain and France are the backup. Málaga is 2 hours from Marrakech by air. Madrid and Barcelona are 2-3 hours. Many retirees schedule specialist consultations and complex procedures in Spain while living in Morocco.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Dental and Optical</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Excellent value. Dental work in Morocco costs 50-70% less than Europe with good quality. Casablanca and Marrakech have modern dental clinics. Eyecare is similarly affordable. Many European expats specifically plan dental work during Morocco stays.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pharmacies</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Well-stocked pharmacies throughout Morocco. Many medications available without prescription. French pharmaceutical standards apply. Prices are low. For specialized medications, bring supplies or arrange from Europe. Pharmacists often speak French.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Cost Planning</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Total Healthcare Budget</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For a 60-year-old retiree: international insurance covering Morocco and Europe ($280-420/month) plus out-of-pocket routine care (300-800 MAD/month, ~$30-80) plus occasional Spain trips for specialist care ($200-500/trip). Total roughly $350-550/month including travel for complex care.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>Use Morocco for routine care:</strong> Doctor visits and medications are very cheap locally. <strong>High deductible:</strong> Self-fund routine care; insure major expenses. <strong>Schedule Europe visits:</strong> Combine family visits with medical appointments to optimize travel costs.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">The Morocco-Europe Lifestyle</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Many retirees live primarily in Morocco (cheap, interesting, warm) but maintain European connections for healthcare, shopping, and family visits. The total cost—even including occasional European healthcare trips—is significantly less than living in Europe full-time.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is Morocco safe for retirees?</h3>
      <p>Morocco is generally safe for tourists and expats. Serious crime against foreigners is rare. Petty theft exists in tourist areas—normal precautions apply. The police presence is visible. Most retirees feel comfortable. Women may receive unwanted attention in some areas but physical safety is rarely a concern.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Do I need to speak French or Arabic?</h3>
      <p>French is widely spoken and essential for daily life outside tourist areas. Arabic is official but French dominates business and educated classes. English is limited—more in tourist areas, rare in healthcare. Learning French makes Morocco significantly more accessible and enjoyable.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I just do visa runs indefinitely?</h3>
      <p>Technically yes—exit to Spain and return for another 90 days. Many expats do this for years. However, it's gray-area and officials can refuse entry if they perceive abuse. For long-term stability, obtaining a residence card is recommended. It also enables car registration, banking, and other practicalities.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">How does healthcare compare to other retirement destinations?</h3>
      <p>Better than Cambodia or Vietnam; not as good as Thailand, Turkey, or South Africa. Casablanca approaches European standards for many conditions. Marrakech is more limited. The key advantage is Europe is 2-3 hours away for anything complex—closer than Southeast Asian destinations to major medical hubs.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Which city is best for retirement?</h3>
      <p>Marrakech: most established expat community, most cultural interest, hot summers. Essaouira: coastal, cooler, more relaxed, artistic. Casablanca: best healthcare, most European, larger city feel. Tangier: closest to Europe, Spanish influence, ferry to Spain. Agadir: beach resort, less character but good climate.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What about Ramadan and Islamic culture?</h3>
      <p>Morocco is Muslim but tolerant of foreigners. Alcohol is available. Western dress is fine in expat areas (modest dress appreciated in medinas). During Ramadan, restaurants in tourist areas remain open; local eating/drinking in public during fasting hours is discouraged. Most retirees adapt easily to cultural norms.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Explore Morocco?"
    description="Get insurance covering Morocco and Europe before your move."
    buttonText="Get Your Morocco Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Visa regulations, healthcare quality, and insurance options change. Verify current requirements with Moroccan authorities. Consider an extended visit before committing to Morocco retirement. Last updated: May 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
